recordings.rmk: Same bird as featured in XC684297 and same comments therein on subspecific attribution apply, repeated as follows: One of two birds in the Harbour Marsh of Sila, a relatively lush and damp patch (reedbed and tamarisks by more or less permanent brackish water) seen intermittently and singing back in response to pishing. To me, this bird sounds very close to those I have recorded much further east in the UAE, eg XC368209, XC307973 and XC633647. The song is essentially a fast reeling with gaps between phrases essentially undetectable to the ear, as they are so short. For that reason, I have tentatively assigned this bird to subsp carpenteri. Graceful Prinia is a quite likely a relatively recent colonist to Sila'a and this subspecies attribution implies colonization from the east, presumably aided by plantations alongside roadsides and in towns in the western Region of the UAE. Purple Sunbird, Red-wattled Lapwing and Grey Francolin are species that have spread westwards in a similar manner. This recording quite different from that attributed to hufufae, such as that by Greg at XC670665. And it dashes any hopes in the UAE that the Sila prinias had got there from the west, ie the eastern region of KSA, where hufufae is resident.
